<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1845,2006]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,216]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="3" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,257,1979,2005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="12">Note</emphasis>
:—The 
<typeStatus box="[347,454,1980,2006]" pageId="3" pageNumber="12">lectotype</typeStatus>
is designated here because the 
<typeStatus box="[822,924,1980,2006]" pageId="3" pageNumber="12">holotype</typeStatus>
at B was destroyed. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,151,177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="13">Etymology</emphasis>
:—The 7-lobed appendage of the gynostegium was used to recognise 
<taxonomicName authority="W.J.Hooker &amp; Arnott, 1834" authorityName="Hooker &amp; Arnott" authorityYear="1834" box="[1171,1311,152,177]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Schistogyne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="4" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1171,1311,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="13">Schistogyne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however, this is the only Bolivian species that presents this characteristic, which is why we chose this epithet.
</paragraph>
